y may be restricted by the Program Authority, usually because they are closely related to the study area of the student’s program."}],"credit_points_header":"6 Units of Credit","eqivalents":[],"exclusion":[],"search_title":"SOMA2481 - Future Screen: Practices of Speculative Media","description":"<p>SOMA2481 <em>Future Screen</em> studies recent and historical examples of science fiction cinema and related critical discourses. The cinematic works include feature films &amp; fictive documentaries, animations and related creative practices such as video art that encompass aspects of science fiction and related genres including horror and fantasy.  Students will view and discuss these examples with reference to a set of readings that will support the creation of a research diary relating to individual areas of studio practice. This diary will then form the basis for a variety of creative responses that can include the creation of a treatment, outline for a studio project, the completion of a related studio project, and/or a comprehensive research essay .</p><p><br /></p>","hb_assessments":[{"delivery_variation":{"cl_id":"2d740c54dbb1fc90be4672f5f3961965","name":"Blended in-person / online - Standard (usually weekly or fortnightly)"},"assessments":[{"individual":{"label":null,"value":null},"assessment_name":"Creative Project","assessment_type":{"label":"Other","value":"other"},"assessment_id":"1","weighting":"40","description":"Students choose between one of two response sto course content. 

Option 1 is the Creative Project developed over the duration of the course and consists of responses that can include the creation of a script treatment, outline for a studio project, short fiction, comic art, screen media works, photography, painting or drawing, and/or the completion of a related studio project. Where the creative response is in written form it must be at least 2,000 words in length. Students will nominate their chosen form for their creative project by Week 6. 

In Option 2 students write a comprehensive research essay of at least 2,000 words [not including notes and bibliography] and will discuss at least two of the course films in relation to one creative aspect of their production such as cinematography, production design, sound etc and discuss how this aspect supports or enhances its narrative, its generic features and its place within wider generic considerations, with reference to course or additional readings.<br />Students are graded [ /40] and offered written feedback using the following marking rubric: 1: A demonstrated knowledge of the form of the response/essay â?? does the form chosen for the creative response suit its content? 2: The quality of the resolution of the project â?? has the response been adequate? Relevant theoretical or contextual interpretation of the response/essay â?? does the response adequately address the conceptual content of the course? Conceptual coherence of the project/essay - does the presentation represent an understanding of the readingâ??s content and arguments? Overall synthesis of ideas in response/essay.","learning_outcomes":[{"value":"CLO1","cl_id":"25740c54dbb1fc90be4672f5f3961966","key":"code"},{"value":"CLO3","cl_id":"25740c54dbb1fc90be4672f5f3961967","key":"code"},{"value":"CLO2","cl_id":"2d740c54dbb1fc90be4672f5f3961966","key":"code"}],"delivery_variations":[],"applies_to_all_delivery_variations":"true","cl_id":"21740c54dbb1fc90be4672f5f396196c","links":[]},{"individual":{"label":null,"value":null},"assessment_name":"Class Presentation","assessment_type":{"label":"Presentation","value":"presentation"},"assessment_id":"2","weighting":"20","description":"Students make a 15-20 minute presentation discussing that weekâ??s film in relation to specific readings related to the film, and/or to one of the general readings on science fiction film. Student&#39;s compare and contrast the opinions and arguments of the reading[s] to the film and offer their own interpretation of the film generally, and to one specific aspect of the film - such as cinematography, production design, sound etc - and discuss how this aspect supports and enhances its narrative.<br />Students are graded [ /20] and offered written feedback using the following marking rubric: 1. Conceptual coherence â??does the presentation represent an understanding of the readingâ??s content and arguments? 2. Relevant theoretical or contextual interpretation â?? does the presentation display an adequate research and an understanding of the researchâ??s relevance?","learning_outcomes":[{"value":"CLO1","cl_id":"25740c54dbb1fc90be4672f5f3961966","key":"code"},{"value":"CLO2","cl_id":"2d740c54dbb1fc90be4672f5f3961966","key":"code"}],"delivery_variations":[],"applies_to_all_delivery_variations":"true","cl_id":"a5740c54dbb1fc90be4672f5f3961968","links":[]},{"individual":{"label":null,"value":null},"assessment_name":"Research Diary","assessment_type":{"label":"Other","value":"other"},"assessment_id":"3","weighting":"40","description":"Students select an area of personal creative interest related to the films under study - e.g. sound, photography, production design, art direction, script, or critical reception and interpretation in various academic texts - and research each film shown in relation to that interest. Students compile a research diary related to the deployment of that creative area in each example. The Research Diary reflects the studentâ??s interests and represents an analytical approach to the material.  Material gathered for the diary is additional to the course readings and can be obtained from any relevant source such as the web, on and offline libraries etc.<br />Students are graded [ /40] and offered written feedback using the following marking rubric:  1: A demonstrated knowledge of the film under discussion â?? does the material presented relate to the film[s]? 2: Relevant theoretical or contextual interpretation of the film components under discussion - does the presentation represent an understanding of the filmâ??s content and readings? 3: Pertinent (visual or textual) research and referencing within the diary format â?? does the diary represent credible research and citation? The first six diary entries will be submitted in in Week 6, the remainder of the entries in Week 13. A progressive mark will be given in Week 7.","learning_outcomes":[{"value":"CLO1","cl_id":"25740c54dbb1fc90be4672f5f3961966","key":"code"},{"value":"CLO2","cl_id":"2d740c54dbb1fc90be4672f5f3961966","key":"code"}],"delivery_variations":[],"applies_to_all_delivery_variations":"true","cl_id":"a9740c54dbb1fc90be4672f5f3961970","links":[]}]}],"inactive_course_alert":null,"timetableURL":"http://timetable.unsw.edu.au/2022/SOMA2481.html","subject_sample_text_staticcontent":"To access course outline, please visit:","links":[]}

